<h1>Problem 1931 - 2024 RMM, P3 of 6</h1>
<h2 class='difficulty'>Difficulty: 9</h2>
<p>Given a positive integer \(n\), a set \(\mathcal{S}\) is \(n\)-admissible if <ul><li>each element of \(\mathcal{S}\) is an unordered triple of integers in \({1, 2, \ldots, n}\),</li><li>\(\lvert \mathcal{S} \rvert = n-2\), and</li><li>for each \(1 \le k \le n - 2\) and each choice of \(k\) distinct \(A_1, A_2, \ldots , A_k \in 
\mathcal{S}\), 
\[\lvert A_1 \cup A_2 \cup  \cdots \cup A_k \rvert \ge k + 2.\]</li></ul>
Is it true that, for all \(n > 3\) and for each \(n\)-admissible set \(\mathcal{S}\), there exist 
pairwise distinct points \(P_1, \ldots, P_n\) in the plane such that the angles of the triangle 
\(P_iP_jP_k\) are all less than \(61^\circ\) for any triple \({i, j, k}\) in \(\mathcal{S}\)?</p>
